<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-632-691  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 632 691.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Dec 1990 v7 n12 p119(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Using Motif's user interface language. (OSF/Motif User InterfaceLanguage) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Flowers, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Programmers can separate the user interface design from thelimitations of a C program for easier customization and quickerprototyping.andP;  By separating the user interface, multiple programscan read in the same user interface description.andP;  Coding is easierbecause the OSF/Motif User Interface Language (UIL) file syntax isnot bound to the syntax of C functions, allowing forwardreferencing of user interface objects.andP;  The design of the userinterface does not depend on whether a programmer uses the UILwith the Toolkit.andP;  A UIL file begins with a module clause thatnames the UIL module and ends with an end module clause.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceProgramming InstructionPrototypeCustom SoftwareTutorialCodingSoftware DesignProgram Development TechniquesC Programming Language.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartprogram.andO;Caption:   A widget hierarchy diagram. (chart)Uiltext example program. (program)C code that reads the UID file. (program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>